2026-04-21 01:40:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module comparator/logic IC or associated RC timing network'] hypothesis_explanation='The lamp dropouts are synchronized with a very small but unstable change at the relay‑drive node, and they disappear completely when the ambient‑light sensor input is hard‑forced to the ‘dark’ state. Adjusting both the timing and sensitivity potentiometers across their full ranges does not eliminate the oscillation when the sensor is left in normal operation. The relay itself remains closed and mechanically stable, and the load module behaves normally when driven steadily. This all localizes the fault to the internal control electronics that interpret the light sensor and generate the relay coil drive. \n\nThe most likely root cause is a defective or marginal comparator/logic IC or a fault in its immediate RC timing/feedback network (e.g., leaky capacitor, wrong or drifting resistor value, or poor bias/reference connection). That subcircuit is causing the relay‑drive output to enter an unintended slow oscillation around threshold, intermittently commanding a brief lamp turn‑off every ~20 seconds. Replacing/repairing the comparator/logic device and its associated timing/reference components in the control (ambient sensor) module should restore stable operation.'
