2026-04-21 01:41:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module light‑sensor bias / reference network configuration'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components and inter‑module cabling test nominal, and forcing the light sensor fully dark removes the symptom while leaving the relay steadily energized and the lamps stable. The comparator/logic IC and its RC timing network have already been replaced/verified without effect, ruling them out. The instability only appears when the light sensor is allowed to operate around its normal threshold, and the comparator output then shows tiny oscillations (~1 mV) and reported non‑convergence, implying the control loop is biased exactly at its switching point with effectively zero hysteresis. Continuity tests confirm that the sensor, its bias resistor, and the relay are intact, but do not validate that the bias/reference network is wired to the correct nodes or with correct values/polarity. The most plausible remaining root cause is a configuration/wiring error or wrong component value in the light‑sensor bias/reference path (e.g., reference resistor tied to the wrong rail, swapped connections to comparator inputs, or an incorrect resistor value), leaving the comparator perched at an indeterminate threshold so that ambient light noise and internal drift cause slow, quasi‑periodic oscillation (20 s period, 0.5 s dropouts). Repair would involve correcting the configuration of the bias/reference network (rewiring to match the intended schematic and verifying resistor values) so that the comparator sees a proper, stable reference and adequate hysteresis around the light sensor signal.'
