2026-04-21 01:41:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient light sensor (LDR/photo‑diode) in control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The only condition under which the 20 s / 0.5 s dropouts disappear is when the ambient‑light sensor input is forcibly overridden (shorted to the bias network to simulate full dark). In that forced‑dark state, the relay drive is rock‑steady around 11.85 V and both lamps remain continuously lit. When the sensor is returned to normal operation at the same ambient light level, the comparator output node shows an unstable or oscillating state and the system reverts to the slow, periodic dropout behavior. \n\nThe timing and sensitivity potentiometers, comparator/logic IC, relay, light‑sensor bias resistor, wiring/continuity of the light‑sensor path, inter‑module cabling, and the 12 V battery have all effectively been ruled out: they either measure nominal or their replacement/adjustment produced no change. The oscillation therefore must be driven by the sensor’s own behavior under normal bias and light, not by its surroundings.\n\nThis points to an intermittent or non‑ideal characteristic in the ambient light sensor itself (e.g., internal leakage, slow relaxation, or non‑linear resistance drift over seconds) that causes the comparator threshold to wander and periodically trip, even though a simple DC resistance measurement (~10 kΩ) looks nominal. Because overriding the sensor cures the issue, replacing the ambient light sensor in the control module is the most specific remaining fault hypothesis consistent with all observations.'
