2026-04-21 01:41:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module internal power / reference decoupling capacitor or RC filter on comparator supply or reference rail'] hypothesis_explanation='All active and passive functional components (battery, lamps, relay, light sensor, bias resistor, potentiometers, comparator/logic IC, wiring and inter‑module cables) have tested nominal, and polarity and connections match the schematic. The oscillation appears only with the normal light‑sensor path active, disappears when the sensor input is hard‑forced to the dark state, and cannot be altered by the timing or sensitivity settings, suggesting the control loop is marginally stable rather than mis‑biased.\n\nThe comparator output node shows tiny oscillatory variation (~1 mV) while logically remaining ‘high’, which is characteristic of a supply or reference rail that is being weakly modulated rather than a digital logic transition. Repeated attempts to measure the control module’s power rails and reference network fail with a simulation “unstable/oscillating” indication, but give no discrete component fault. This strongly points to a decoupling or RC filter component whose value is wrong (too large or too small) or missing, thereby creating an unintended long RC time constant and low‑frequency oscillation between the comparator, relay coil current draw, and its supply/reference.\n\nBecause all discrete, testable elements around the light sensor and feedback network are reported correct and wiring continuity/polarity is verified, the remaining plausible root cause is a faulty or mis‑valued decoupling or RC filter capacitor (or closely associated resistor) on the comparator’s supply or sensor reference rail internal to the control module. Replacing this small-signal power/reference conditioning network should eliminate the 20 s / 0.5 s periodic dropouts without altering the rest of the circuit behavior.'
