2026-04-21 01:42:41 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module series protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='All three modules’ active control elements, wiring, power rails, lamps, relay and sensor network have been systematically tested and found nominal and stable. The PSU voltage is steady, the relay coil drive and contacts remain effectively constant, and both lamps behave as simple resistive loads with correct resistances and nearly full supply voltage across them, even when the dropout is observed.\n\nThis narrows the remaining unique element in the load path to the series protection diode in the load module (between the control module output and both lamps). An intermittent or marginal failure of this diode (e.g., junction temporarily going high‑impedance or exhibiting sporadic conduction collapse under load or temperature) would cause the entire lamp current to momentarily cease, turning both the main lamp and the internal indicator off for brief intervals, without significantly disturbing the upstream supply voltages or relay state. Because the diode is after all previously tested elements, its intermittent behavior would not show up in continuity or static voltage checks when it is in its normal conducting state.\n\nTherefore the most plausible single root cause consistent with all observations is a faulty series protection diode in the load module. Replacing/repairing this diode (or its immediate connections) should resolve the 0.5 s lamp dropouts while leaving the rest of the system unchanged.'
