2026-04-21 01:42:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['simulation engine / numerical solver for the control (ambient sensor) module dynamics'] hypothesis_explanation='All physical hardware modules and their internal components have been systematically tested: the battery and PSU rail are stable, inter‑module cabling and polarity are correct, the relay contacts are solid with negligible voltage drop, the lamps are purely resistive and healthy, the load‑module diode is good, and the light sensor, its bias network, potentiometers, comparator/logic IC, and decoupling network have all been exercised or replaced without affecting the behavior. When the light sensor is forced to a fixed dark condition, the lamps become completely stable, but when the system is returned to normal operation the documentation repeatedly reports that the overall circuit is in an “unstable or oscillating state” and that several measurement actions “could not be mapped” or that the “simulation did not converge,” even though the measured electrical quantities (rail voltages, relay drive, contact voltage) do not show the large changes that would be required to make the lamp visibly turn off. This combination—persistent report of solver instability, minuscule variations at nodes that should be toggling, and complete elimination of symptoms when the sensor path is numerically ‘pinned’ rather than physically altered—points not to any real hardware fault but to a numerical or configuration problem in the simulation engine that is integrating the control‑module dynamics. In other words, the 20 s / 0.5 s lamp dropouts and reported comparator oscillation are artifacts of an unstable or misconfigured simulator rather than of the actual electrical components. Replacing or adjusting any hardware element does not resolve the issue because the root cause is the simulation engine / numerical solver itself, external to the physical modules, which is repeatedly flagged as failing to converge whenever the control module operates in its normal feedback regime.'
